@node "What" "What is AmiyDec?"

                                What is AmiyDec?
                                ================

AmiyDec is a utility for decoding yEnc encoded files which are becoming
more popular on places like Usenet. yEnc is similar in principle to UUencoded
or Base64 encoded files which you may be more familiar with. Base64 and UUencode
convert binary files into 7bit ASCII for transmission over services which do not
allow binary such as E-Mail. Usenet however allows many 8bit ASCII character and
yEnc takes advantage of this. The resulting encoded file is significantly
smaller than the UUencoded or Base65 encoded version.
    For example a small test with a 512k file produced these results:

        UUencoded: 718.2k
        Base64   : 693.4k
        yEnc     : 522.9k

For additional information, please see http://www.yenc.org

@endnode
@node "Usage" "Usage"

                                     Usage
                                     =====

AmiyDec is based around the yEnc v1.3 specification including support for
CRC32 checksumming, if the encoded file uses it. It currently does not yet
support multi-part encodings. If the encoding is contained in a message saved
from a newsreader for example, you do not have to strip out anything unrelated
to yEnc. AmiyDec handles this automatically.

    amiydec <input file> <output directory> [DEBUG]

Input file is the encoded file you wish to decode, and output directory is the
destination you wish to write the file to. You do not specify the output
filename because it is already contained in the encoding. The optional keyword
DEBUG may be specified to display information about the decoding. You can test
AmiyDec by trying it on the supplied yEnc file 'test.ync' . The decoded file
is a binary which prints a message.

Examples:

    amiydec tesy.ync RAM:
    amiydec misc.ync Work:myfiles/ DEBUG


@endnode
@node "Caveats" "Caveats"

                                    Caveats
                                    =======

1. If the input file contains more than one yEnc encoded file, it will only
decode the first. (Note: Not to be confused with multi-part encodings). You
can get around this by chopping the first yEnc header and running the file
through AmiyDec again.

2. Several broken encoders exist. Please ensure that the encoding was not made
by one of these broken encoders before making a bug report.

Broken Encoders:
NNTP POWER POST 2000 (Build 25b; yEnc) (creating crc32=00000001 as default)
NNTP POWER POST 2000 (Build 24c)
yPost / 0.45 (The part= paramater is missing in the =yend line for multiparts)
MT Newswatcher 3.2 (creating =ypart begin=0 .... end=<filesize>)


@endnode
@node "Errors" "Error Messages"

                                 Error Messages
                                 ==============

1. [Warning: File size mismatch between header and decoded file]

   This means the file size stated in the yEnc header does not match the decoded
   file's size. The yEnc encoding has probably been corrupted meaning the
   resulting decoded file is probably corrupt.

2. [Warning: CRC32 mismatch]

   The CRC32 checksum stated in the yEnc header does not match the CRC32
   checksum calculated by AmigyDec. The yEnc encoding has probably been
   corrupted or was created by a broken encoder. The decoded file will
   probably be corrupt.

3. [Invalid Header: Missing filename parameter]

   The filename parameter is compulsory and is missing from the yEnc header.
   Decoding is aborted.

4. [Unable to open input file]

   Could be for various reasons including, not existant file, file is read
   locked, or some other miscellaneous disk error.

5. [Unable to open output file]

   Could be for various reasons including, destination is write-protected, write
   locked, or some other miscellaneous disk error.

6. [Unable to allocate memory for buffer]

   A large enough block of memory is not available to load your file either
   because you do not have enough free memory, or it has become highly fragmented.

7. [Unable to read all of the input file]

   The input file was partially read, but could not continue, probably because
   of a disk error. Decoding is aborted.

8. [File does not contain a valid yEnc encoding]

   AmiyDec could not find a yEnc header in the input file.

9. [Premature end of encoding]

   AmiyDec did not find a valid yEnc trailer before it encountered the end of
   the file. The decoded file is probably corrupt.

10. [Unknown exception]

   AmiyDec encountered an exception it did not recognise. Please report it to
   me including the exception value.

11. [Appears to be a multipart yEnc encoding. Not yet supported]

    The yEnc encoded file is part of a multi-part yEnc encoding. Multi-part
    decodings are not supported in this release.

@endnode
@node "Contact" "Contact"

                                    Contact
                                    =======


E-Mail: ian.chapman@bleach.demon.co.uk

If you wish to make a bug report, please ensure that you are not trying to
decode a file which was created with a broken encoder. See @{" Caveats " Link "Caveats"}

It may also be useful to send me the output when decoding the file using the
DEBUG option, or possibly also sending me the encoded file. Please do not send
files larger than 150K.

@endnode

